# CEM — System Architecture Stage Specification

This document defines System Architecture as a general, reusable part of the CEM pipeline. Unlike the earlier
stages, it is not primarily a document to write — it is a **task tree generated from Released Decision
Records**, where each task's job is to find or fabricate the actual thing a decision called for, and record
what was found or built.

```
Decision Records
    │
    ▼
System Architecture   ← this document
    │
    ▼
Generated Project
```

## 1. Purpose

Decision Records answers: *why was this chosen, and is the choice trustworthy?*
System Architecture answers: *how does the chosen thing actually get into existence — sourced or built?*

A System Architecture Task never re-argues why something was chosen — that stays in Decision Records,
referenced by ID. A task only ever describes fulfillment: locate a vendor part, or build a thing from
materials, some of which may themselves need to be located or built.

## 2. Task generation

Exactly one top-level **Task** is generated per **Released** Decision Record — not per Requirements row, and
not before Released. Before a decision is Released there is nothing concrete enough to task out yet (see the
Decision Records spec, §6).

A task's **Type** — **Buy** or **Make** — is inherited directly from the Decision Record's Make-vs-Buy flag.

## 3. Materials and recursion

Every task carries a **material list**:

- A **Buy** task's material list has exactly one line: the finished item itself.
- A **Make** task's material list is the actual bill of materials — every part or raw material the build
  consumes.

Each material line has a **Source Type**, resolved *per quantity*, not per line as a whole:

| Source Type | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Stock** | Already on hand — covers as much of the needed quantity as is actually available |
| **Buy** | Remaining quantity not covered by Stock is purchased directly |
| **Make** | Remaining quantity not covered by Stock requires its own fabrication step |

**If any quantity remains unfulfilled by Stock, that remainder spawns a child Task** (Buy or Make, matching
the material's Source Type), scoped only to the shortfall quantity — not the full requirement. A child task
has exactly the same structure as any other task: its own Type, its own material list, and its own children
if its materials in turn need sourcing. This is what makes System Architecture a genuine multi-level BOM
rather than a flat list — recursion bottoms out only when every remaining material line is fully covered by
Stock or is a directly-sourceable Buy with no further decomposition.

### Worked micro-example

Recharging Controller (`DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001`, Type: Make) needs 20 units of a connector housing as one of
its materials. 3 are already in stock.

```
Task  SA:DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001              (Make)
  └─ Material  ...M01  Connector housing, qty needed: 20
       Stock: 3  →  covers 3
       Remainder: 17  →  Source Type: Buy  →  spawns child task
           └─ Task  SA:DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001/M01/T01     (Buy, qty: 17)
```

Only the shortfall (17) is tasked out. The 3 in stock never re-enter the sourcing process.

## 4. IDs

- **Task ID:** `SA:<Decision ID>` for a top-level task (e.g. `SA:DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001`).
- **Material ID:** `<Task ID>/M<sequence>` (e.g. `SA:DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001/M01`).
- **Child Task ID:** `<Material ID>/T<sequence>` (e.g. `.../M01/T01`), used when a material's remainder needs
  its own fabrication or purchasing step. A child task's own materials continue the same pattern one level
  deeper, however many levels the BOM actually requires.

Reading a full ID top to bottom shows the entire lineage from Decision Record to the deepest raw material.

## 5. Task Status (lifecycle)

```
Open
  │
  ▼
Sourcing
  │
  ▼
Partially Fulfilled
  │
  ▼
Fulfilled
  │
  ▼
Received / Verified
  │
  ▼
Complete
```

| State | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Open** | Task generated, not yet started |
| **Sourcing** | Actively searching (Buy) or building (Make) |
| **Partially Fulfilled** | Some material lines resolved, others still have open child tasks |
| **Fulfilled** | Every material line is covered — all child tasks Complete or lines were Stock/direct-Buy |
| **Received / Verified** | The fulfilled item has been physically received or the build physically confirmed |
| **Complete** | Task closed; feeds the Generated Project artifact record |

**Task Status is not the same gate as Decision Records' Evidence Required.** Evidence Required asks whether
the *decision* is trustworthy (certification, test results, approvals). Task Status asks whether the *thing*
has been sourced or built yet. A task can reach Fulfilled — the part is in hand — while its parent Decision
Record's Evidence Required checklist is still incomplete (e.g. certification hasn't arrived). The two are
tracked independently and both must clear before a project can be considered done.

## 6. What System Architecture never contains

- No re-statement of why a candidate was chosen — that's a reference to the Decision ID, not a repeated
  Reason field.
- No editing of upstream Requirements or Concept Architecture. If a task discovers that a chosen candidate
  can't actually be sourced or built as specified, that is fed back as a new Decision Record (see the Decision
  Records spec, §7, Supersession) — never as a silent change here.

## 7. Handoff to Generated Project

Once every top-level task reaches Complete, the collected material and build records for a subsystem become
its entry in the Generated Project artifact set — the actual BOM, vendor list, and/or build documentation that
a person or downstream tool (CAD, PLC, code generator) consumes.
